eligion is a 'less compelling reason&quot; is almost an insult ... for many it is foremost in their minds.   In a capitalistic system people not only vote through ballots, they vote with their feet. If I don't care for a product or a company, I simply take my business elsewhere. The same is true for schools.   Leave it to the &quot;liberal mind&quot; to label people &quot;bad&quot; for disagreeing with them. I still prefer showerheads with some power, toilets that flush, and incandescent lighting, too. I'm simply not prepared to march, lock-step, into another person's life choices and make them mine.   Orwell had a handle on thing to come when he coined the phrases, &quot;newspeak&quot; and &quot;double-speak&quot;. It's actually become politically incorrect to address some very real issues. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1055" language="en" documentId="2438" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Sails" date="Aug 29, 2013 11:29PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="20" thumbsDown="0" origId="2438" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1055"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>